5 Basic Plotting!

5.1 Year painted vs.year acquired

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(moma, aes(x = year_created, y = year_acquired))+
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2, na.rm = T)+
  geom_abline(color = "red", intercept = c(0,0))+
  labs(x = "Year Painted", y = "Year Acquired")+
  ggtitle("MoMA Keeps Its Collection Current", subtitle = "Year of a work's acquisition vs. year it was painted, for works acquired since 1930")

5.2 Faceting by gender

solo_moma = moma %>% filter(num_artists == 1)


ggplot(solo_moma, aes(x = year_created, y = year_acquired))+
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2, na.rm = T)+
  geom_abline(color = "red", intercept = c(0,0))+
  labs(x = "Year Painted", y = "Year Acquired")+
  ggtitle("MoMA Keeps Its Collection Current", subtitle = "Year of a work's acquisition vs. year it was painted, for works acquired since 1930")+
  facet_wrap(~artist_gender)

6 Exploring Painting Dimensions

moma2 = moma %>% filter(width_cm<760 & height_cm<600) %>% 
  mutate(taller = case_when(height_cm > width_cm ~ "taller", 
                            height_cm < width_cm ~ "wider",
                            height_cm == width_cm ~ "square"))

ggplot(moma2, aes(x = width_cm, y = height_cm, col = taller))+
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5)+
  ggtitle("MoMA Paintings, Tall and Wide")+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

6.3 Experimenting with geom_annotate()

ggplot(moma2, aes(x = width_cm, y = height_cm, col = taller))+
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5)+
  ggtitle("MoMA Paintings, Tall and Wide")+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")+
  labs(x = "Width", y = "Height")+
  theme_fivethirtyeight()+

                     values = c("gray50", "#ee5863", "#6999cd"))+
  annotate(x = 390, y = 100, geom = "text", label = "Wider than \n Tall", color = "#6999cd",size = 5, family = "Lato", fontface = 2)+
  annotate(x = 150, y = 370, geom = "text", label = "Taller than \n Wide", color = "#ee5863",size = 5, family = "Lato", fontface = 2)

7 Challenge #5, on your own!

I made a plot to see the changes in proportion of acquired paintings for sex over time. The proportion would give me a sense of the dominance of male artists rather than the count. I could see there is an increasing trend of the proportion of female artists paintings over time.

solo_moma$artist_gender_fct = factor(solo_moma$artist_gender)
solo_moma$artist_gender_fct = fct_relevel(solo_moma$artist_gender_fct, "Male")


ggplot(solo_moma, aes(x = year_acquired, col = artist_gender_fct))+
 geom_bar(aes(fill = artist_gender_fct), position = "fill", colour = "white", alpha = 0.5)+
 labs(x = "Year acquired", y = "Proportion")+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2", name = "")+
  ggtitle("The Proportion of Acquired MoMA Paintings \n for Artist Gender Over Time")+
  theme_fivethirtyeight()+
  annotate(x = 1988, y = 0.42, geom = "point", col = "red")+
  annotate('segment', x = 1988, xend =1988, y = 0.52, yend = 0.42, col = "red")+
  annotate('text', x = 1972, y = 0.56, label = "Acquired 7 paintings by female artists during 1987 and 1988", size = 3.5)+
  
  annotate(x = 2004, y = 0.6, geom = "point", col = "red")+
  annotate('segment', x = 2004, xend =2004, y = 0.7, yend = 0.6, col = "red")+
  annotate('text', x = 1980, y = 0.74, label = "Acquired 31 paintings by female artists during 2004 and 2005", size = 3.5)
